<div id="main-article" class="article-content retro-folders">
<p></p><div class="quoteright" style="width:341px;"><div class="lazy_load_img_box" style="padding-top:155.13%"><img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/images/Fantomas1911_1355.jpg" class="embeddedimage" border="0" alt="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/images/Fantomas1911_1355.jpg" width="341" height="529"></div></div><div class="proper-ad-unit mobile-ad square_ad"><h6 class="ad-caption">Advertisement:</h6><div id="proper-ad-tvtropes_mobile_ad_1"><script>propertag.cmd.push(function() { proper_display('tvtropes_mobile_ad_1'); })</script></div></div><p>The character of Fant&ocirc;mas was created in 1911 by Marcel Allain and Pierre Souvestre for a series of <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheEdwardianEra" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheEdwardianEra">turn-of-the-(20th)-century</a> French novels.</p><p>In the original version, Fant&ocirc;mas &mdash; the name comes from the French words "<em>fant&ocirc;me</em>", meaning "phantom" or "ghost" and "<em>as</em>", meaning "ace" &mdash; is an anarchist whose crimes are (supposedly) a result of his disdain for modern civilization; he is chased by a <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SympatheticInspectorAntagonist" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SympatheticInspectorAntagonist">police detective named Juve</a> and a journalist, <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeathByOriginStory" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DeathByOriginStory">Charles Rambert</a>/<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IntrepidReporter" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IntrepidReporter">J&eacute;r&ocirc;me Fandor</a>, but in spite of a few close calls, he is never caught. The novels were adapted for film many times; ironically, the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Fantomas" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Fantomas">most popular adaptation by Andr&eacute; Hunebelle</a> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/WeirdAlEffect" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/WeirdAlEffect">is a parody</a>.</p><p>The first few novels were co-written by Pierre Souvestre (1874-1914), and Marcel Allain (1885-1969). The early death of Souvestre resulted in subsequent novels written by Allain alone. The literal translations of the original French titles are based on the list of Jean-Marc Lofficier.</p><div class="proper-ad-unit mobile-ad square_ad"><h6 class="ad-caption">Advertisement:</h6><div id="proper-ad-tvtropes_mobile_ad_2"><script>propertag.cmd.push(function() { proper_display('tvtropes_mobile_ad_2'); })</script></div></div><ul><li> <em>Fant&ocirc;mas</em> (1911)</li><li> <em>Juve vs. Fant&ocirc;mas</em> (1911)</li><li> <em>The Dead Man Who Kills</em> (1911), also known as <em>The Vengeance of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The Secret Agent</em> (1911), also known as <em>A Ruse of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>A King Prisoner of Fant&ocirc;mas</em> (1911)</li><li> <em>The Apache Policeman</em> (1911), also known as <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Policeman</em></li><li> <em>The Hanged Man of London</em> (1911), also known as <em>In the Hands of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The Daughter of Fant&ocirc;mas</em> (1911)</li><li> <em>The Night Hansom Cab</em> (1911), also known as <em>The Hansom Cab of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The Severed Hand</em> (1911), also known as <em>Fant&ocirc;mas in Monaco</em></li><li> <em>The Capture of Fant&ocirc;mas</em> (1911)</li><li> <em>The Burglar Judge</em> (1912), also known as <em>Judge Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The Livery of Crime</em> (1912), also known as <em>The Livery of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The Death of Juve</em> (1912), also known as <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Kills Juve</em></li><li> <em>The Escapee from Saint-Lazare</em> (1912), also known as <em>Fant&ocirc;mas, King of Crime</em></li><li> <em>The Disappearance of Fandor</em> (1912), also known as <em>Fandor vs. Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><div class="proper-ad-unit mobile-ad square_ad"><h6 class="ad-caption">Advertisement:</h6><div id="proper-ad-tvtropes_mobile_ad_3"><script>propertag.cmd.push(function() { proper_display('tvtropes_mobile_ad_3'); })</script></div></div><li> <em>The Wedding of Fant&ocirc;mas</em> (1912)</li><li> <em>The Assassin of Lady Beltham</em> (1912), also known as <em>The Loves of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The Red Wasp</em> (1912), also known as <em>The Challenge of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The Dead Man's Shoes</em> (1912), also known as <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Prowls</em></li><li> <em>The Lost Train</em> (1912), also known as <em>The Train of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The Love of a Prince</em> (1912), also known as <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Has Fun</em></li><li> <em>The Tragic Bouquet</em> (1912), also known as <em>The Bouquet of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The Masked Jockey</em> (1913), also known as <em>Fant&ocirc;mas, King of the Turf</em></li><li> <em>The Empty Coffin</em> (1913), also known as <em>The Coffin of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The Queen Maker</em> (1913), also known as <em>Fant&ocirc;mas vs. Love</em></li><li> <em>The Giant Corpse</em> (1913), also known as <em>The Spectre of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The Gold Thief</em> (1913), also known as <em>Prisoners of Fant&ocirc;mas!</em></li><li> <em>The Red Series</em> (1913), also known as <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Escapes</em></li><li> <em>Crime Hotel</em> (1913), also known as <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Accuses!</em></li><li> <em>The Hemp Necktie</em> (1913), also known as <em>The Servant of Fant&ocirc;mas</em></li><li> <em>The End of Fant&ocirc;mas</em> (1913), also known as <em>Is Fant&ocirc;mas Dead?</em></li><li> <em>Is Fant&ocirc;mas Resurrected?</em> (1925)</li><li> <em>Fant&ocirc;mas, King of the Fences</em> (1926)</li><li> <em>Fant&ocirc;mas in Danger</em> (1926)</li><li> <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Takes His Revenge</em> (1926)</li><li> <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Attacks Fandor</em> (1926)</li><li> <em>If It Was Fant&ocirc;mas?</em> (1933)</li><li> <em>Yes, It Is Fant&ocirc;mas!</em> (1934)</li><li> <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Plays and Wins</em> (1935)</li><li> <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Meets Love</em> (1946)</li><li> <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Steals from the Blondes</em> (1948)</li><li> <em>Fant&ocirc;mas Leads the Dance</em> (1963)</li></ul><hr><h2><em>Fant&ocirc;mas</em> provides examples of:</h2><p></p><ul><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AxCrazy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AxCrazy">Ax-Crazy</a>: As sophisticated and suave as the man is, it&#146;s clear that at least some of his crimes are motivated by little more than a lust for bloodshed.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ActionGirl" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ActionGirl">Action Girl</a>: H&eacute;l&egrave;ne, Fant&ocirc;mas' daughter, has her moments.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheBadGuyWins" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheBadGuyWins">The Bad Guy Wins</a>: In <em>A King Prisoner of Fant&ocirc;mas</em>, Fant&ocirc;mas convinces the world at large that inspector Juve is just another of his own identities. Resulting in Juve facing prison time, and Fandor becoming a runaway fugitive. The situation is maintained in at least part of <em>The Apache Policeman</em>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BrotherSisterIncest" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BrotherSisterIncest">Brother&#150;Sister Incest</a>: Fandor and H&eacute;l&egrave;ne have the hots for each other. They are respectively Fant&ocirc;mas' alleged son and daughter. Making them half-siblings. Fant&ocirc;mas may have a reason for keeping them apart.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/CoatHatMask" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/CoatHatMask">Coat, Hat, Mask</a></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Crossdresser" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Crossdresser">Crossdresser</a>: H&eacute;l&egrave;ne, Fant&ocirc;mas' daughter, wears masculine clothes, and frequently poses as a man. Though whether she is a villainous or sympathetic character depends on the novel.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DaddysLittleVillain" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DaddysLittleVillain">Daddy's Little Villain</a>: Toyed with in the person of H&eacute;l&egrave;ne, Fant&ocirc;mas' daughter. H&eacute;l&egrave;ne has her own criminal activities, though nominally loyal to her father. She spends many stories trying to equally avoid her possessive father and the long arm of the law. Though her mutual attraction with Fandor further complicates things. The writers made an effort to portray her as a bad girl, with her skull-shaped tattoo, habit of smoking opium, and cross-dressing tendencies.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DetectiveMole" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DetectiveMole">Detective Mole</a>: In <em>The Hanged Man of London</em> (1911), Fant&ocirc;mas himself has infiltrated <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/ScotlandYard" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/ScotlandYard">Scotland Yard</a> and serves as one of its top detectives.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EscapeArtist" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EscapeArtist">Escape Artist</a>: Both Fant&ocirc;mas and H&eacute;l&egrave;ne escape arrest and/or death numerous times.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EveryoneIsASuspect" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EveryoneIsASuspect">Everyone Is a Suspect</a>: Fant&ocirc;mas himself, his daughter H&eacute;l&egrave;ne, and his main lover Lady Maud Beltham change disguises and identities with particular ease. Meaning that every character could be one of them in disguise. Fant&ocirc;mas was at some point revealed to maintain an identity as a top detective for <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/ScotlandYard" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/ScotlandYard">Scotland Yard</a>, and Beltham an identity as Mother Superior of a convent. And Fandor was shocked to learn that his athletic friend Teddy, was actually H&eacute;l&egrave;ne in disguise.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FakingTheDead" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FakingTheDead">Faking the Dead</a>: Fant&ocirc;mas has faked the demise of one or more of his identities at various times. Most notably when faking the death of &Eacute;tienne Rambert. He boards (or appears to be boarding) the trans-Atlantic passenger liner Lancaster. Then arranges for the ship to sink in mid-voyage. Rambert is reported dead, among many other victims of the disaster.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FlayingAlive" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FlayingAlive">Flaying Alive</a>: Scalping variation. In <em>The Escapee from Saint-Lazare</em> (1912), Fant&ocirc;mas decides to kill Blanche Perrier, mistress of one of his previous victims. She has beautiful long hair. He catches said hair in a machine and scalps her.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FrightDeathTrap" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FrightDeathTrap">Fright Death Trap</a>: Toyed with in <em>The Severed Hand</em> (1911). Fant&ocirc;mas captures aristocrat Isabelle de Guerray. He keeps her blindfolded, and threatens to kill her, if she doesn't offer information on the safety measures protecting her fortune. At some point Isabelle feels a knife blade touching her arm and warm liquid, apparently her own blood, flowing down. She is literally scared to death. Juve later discovers that there is not a scratch on her body. The knife never really cut her, the warm liquid was mere water.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IHaveManyNames" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IHaveManyNames">I Have Many Names</a>: The real name of Fant&ocirc;mas is never revealed. But the readers learn that he has used many names over the years. Among them:<ul><li> Archduke Juan North. A name he used while active among the German nobility c. 1892.</li><li> Sergeant Gurn. A name he used while serving as an artillery sergeant in <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/TheSecondBoerWar" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/TheSecondBoerWar">The Second Boer War</a> (1899-1902).</li><li> &Eacute;tienne Rambert. Name of a former business partner of his, who was also father to Charles Rambert/J&eacute;r&ocirc;me Fandor. He claimed the identity to further his own plots.</li></ul></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/InfantImmortality" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/InfantImmortality">Infant Immortality</a>: Averted in <em>The Hanged Man of London</em> (1911). Lady Beltham and prostitute Nini Guinon are having an intense argument over the fate of a baby. Nini seizes the slumbering baby and drives a "dagger into his chest. Before baby Daniel drew another breath, a torrent of bright blood spewed from his wound. Immediately his lips went pale."</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheInfiltration" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheInfiltration">The Infiltration</a>: Both Juve and Fandor at times pose as "apaches" (members of the Parisian underworld) to pass unnoticed among their numbers.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/InnerMonologue" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/InnerMonologue">Inner Monologue</a>: Used as exposition very often. Fant&ocirc;mas would also often "talk" to his cat to express his feelings. (The cat would sometimes be shown thinking, although this was a metafictional device; it was not shown to actually be intelligent.)</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/KarmaHoudini" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/KarmaHoudini">Karma Houdini</a>: Fant&ocirc;mas</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LukeIAmYourFather" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LukeIAmYourFather">Luke, I Am Your Father</a>: A variation. In <em>The End of Fant&ocirc;mas</em>, <span class="spoiler" title="you can set spoilers visible by default on your profile">Fant&ocirc;mas reveals to Inspector Juve that they are twin brothers.</span></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LukeIMightBeYourFather" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LukeIMightBeYourFather">Luke, I Might Be Your Father</a>: One of the major twists of <em>Fant&ocirc;mas</em> (1911) is that Fant&ocirc;mas had been posing as &Eacute;tienne Rambert. But the duration of the ruse is left uncertain. The real Rambert might have been out of the picture for decades. J&eacute;r&ocirc;me Fandor, supposed son of Rambert, may actually be a biological son of Fant&ocirc;mas. The series never gave a definite answer on the subject.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MalevolentMaskedMen" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MalevolentMaskedMen">Malevolent Masked Men</a>: Fant&ocirc;mas is sometimes depicted wearing a domino mask.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MasterOfDisguise" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MasterOfDisguise">Master of Disguise</a>: Per discription: "Fant&ocirc;mas is nearly always disguised as someone else, often several people in the same novel episode."... "One master criminal with a thousand faces".</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MeaningfulName" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MeaningfulName">Meaningful Name</a>: <em>Fant&ocirc;mas</em> is quite fitting for one of the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TropeCodifier" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TropeCodifier">Trope Codifiers</a> of <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PhantomThief" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PhantomThief">Phantom Thief</a>.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/NietzscheWannabe" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/NietzscheWannabe">Nietzsche Wannabe</a>: Fant&ocirc;mas</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ObfuscatingDisability" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ObfuscatingDisability">Obfuscating Disability</a>: In <em>The Death of Juve</em> (1912), Juve spends months acting as if completely paralyzed, following an earlier encounter with his foe. When Fant&ocirc;mas finally pays him a visit, the villain is caught off-guard. Juve lunges from his bed, tackles him, and wrestles him to the ground. Juve had been exaggerating the extend of his injuries for quite some time.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OffWithHisHead" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OffWithHisHead">Off with His Head!</a>: The original novel apparently concludes with the decapitation of Fant&ocirc;mas at the guillotine. Until the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TwistEnding" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TwistEnding">Twist Ending</a> reveals <span class="spoiler" title="you can set spoilers visible by default on your profile">that the man executed was actually Valgrand, a theatrical actor who was playing Fant&ocirc;mas on stage.</span> The real Fant&ocirc;mas had left an innocent man to die in his place.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OverlordJr" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OverlordJr">Overlord Jr.</a>: Vladimir, son of Fant&ocirc;mas. He is also a career criminal, and a ruthless murderer, but has little of his father's brilliance.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PapaWolf" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PapaWolf">Papa Wolf</a>: Fant&ocirc;mas seems to genuinely care for H&eacute;l&egrave;ne, and goes out of his way to protect her when needed. Though his love is "jealous and possessive", and he tries to keep H&eacute;l&egrave;ne and Fandor apart.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PhantomThief" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PhantomThief">Phantom Thief</a>: This guy is what happens when one of these characters goes very, <em>very</em> bad.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RedBaron" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RedBaron">Red Baron</a>: Fant&ocirc;mas has nicknames/titles such as Genius of Evil, Lord of Terror, Master of Crime.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheStarscream" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheStarscream">The Starscream</a>: Toyed with in <em>The Death of Juve</em> (1912). Juve manages to capture Fant&ocirc;mas and ties up the villain. He then summons the nearest police officer and goes seeking further help. Said "officer" is actually an agent of Fant&ocirc;mas, but is quite willing to betray his boss. But then a contingency plan of Fant&ocirc;mas pays off. A timed firebomb explodes elsewhere in the building. The double-crosser figures that Fant&ocirc;mas is the only one who could safely lead him out of the burning building. He unties Fant&ocirc;mas... and is then quickly murdered by his irate boss.</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/VillainBasedFranchise" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/VillainBasedFranchise">Villain-Based Franchise</a></li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/VillainProtagonist" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/VillainProtagonist">Villain Protagonist</a></li></ul><hr>
</div>
